    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="319"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AD/7–1850: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Political Adviser in Japan</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sebald</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-18">July 18,
                            1950</date>.<lb/>[Received July 18—8:33 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Unnumbered. For <gloss target="#t_OAFE1">OAFE</gloss> and State Department. Re
                    State Department message 180106Z (sent Tokyo as 102).<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d319fn1">Transmitted on July 17 at 6 p. m., <ref target="#pg_411">p.
                            411</ref>.</note> I have discussed matter with General MacArthur who in
                    effect states as follows:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“General MacArthur holds Secretary Romulo in highest esteem and personal
                        regard, but the military situation in Korea does not permit this type of
                        activity at this time. A further objection is the fact that he is the
                        Foreign Minister of the Philippine Islands Republic and has no connection
                        with the UN Commission on Korea. It is believed that his, presence would
                        tend to create friction and misunderstanding which at this time would
                        certainly be most undesirable. If his services are to be employed in the
                        Korean situation it should manifestly be from his UN Headquarters rather
                        than Korea. If any opportunity presents itself in the future to utilize his
                        services here, it will be reported at once.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sebald</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
